DIE-OFF, CERVID - SPAIN (02): (CASTILE AND LEON) REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Tue 10 Aug 2010
Source: La Opinion de Zamora [in Spanish, trans. Corr.SB, summ., edited]
<http://www.laopiniondezamora.es/comarcas/2010/08/10/junta-admite-mortandad-debe-enfermedad-infecciosa/455267.html>

The territorial delegate to the Junta [provincial government] of Castile
and Leon in Zamora, Alberto Castro, said yesterday [9 Aug 2010] that the
cause of death of the up to now 79 red deer in the Sierra de la Culebra is
still unknown, but confirmed that it is an infectious disease that affects
exclusively red deer. Tests conducted last week [week of 2 Aug 2010] were
"inconclusive", but bluetongue and "common diseases" such as epizootic
haemorrhagic disease have been ruled out.

Of the 79 deaths recorded up to yesterday [9 Aug 2010], 36 were in the
Regional Game Reserve and 43 in 18 affected private reserves. The Junta has
used the protocols of the animal health laboratories in Leon and Algete
(Madrid) for the analysis of samples. It has also started collaboration
with the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine of the University of Leon.

Castro justifies the slow pace of investigation because in the case of
diseases of wild animals, "this is not an exact science, with the added
constraint that when [the dead deer] are found they have been decomposing
for a long time." According to what he has been told by veterinarians,
"when a wild animal is sick, he/she hides in inaccessible areas, making the
task [of locating them] difficult. The vultures preying on them indicate
their location but they may not be found until several days later."

The Junta of Castile and Leon has all its resources working "100 per cent"
to search for the origin [of the disease] and to take action. "Samples
taken last week [week of 2 Aug 2010] have been negative but we will
intensify the search for high-quality samples from sick animals, and we
will comb the mountains."

The message to farmers is reassuring, "because the [dead] deer are being
found in higher areas of the mountain where farmers do not graze sheep or
goats. Bluetongue is a disease of concern, which might have spread to
domestic animals, but it has been ruled out [in this instance]." Finally,
authorities called for "responsibility and prudence to avoid speculation"
and said the results will be made public as soon as they become available
and that any person may request information from the Ministry of
Agriculture and Livestock.

[byline: Nerea Villoria]

--
