******
[2]
Date: Tue 10 Aug 2010
Source: Leonoticias.com [in Spanish, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
<http://leonoticias.com/frontend/leonoticias/La-Junta-Pide-Ayuda-A-La-Universidad-Para-Determinar-Que-Vir-vn53467-vst218>


Juan Francisco Marin, former dean of the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine of
Leon, said today [10 Aug 2010] that the deaths of red deer in the provinces
of Leon and especially Zamora could be due to the recurrence of an outbreak
of a bacterial infectious disease previously registered in Spain, in 1991,
in the Montes Universales on the border between Aragon and Castile-La
Mancha, as well as in other countries, such as the United States.

Although Marin said he has not directly examined any of the animals that
have died his hypothesis is based on known data and considers this could be
a "similar situation" to that caused by the infectious disease that appears
"especially in summer" and that affects mainly red deer, but also wild
ruminants and occasionally mouflon [a breed of sheep. - Mod.PC] He also
recalled the 1991 outbreak in the Montes Universales that caused a
mortality of more than 100 animals. [Marin] acknowledged that sometimes a
disease "takes time to diagnose", but emphasized that once [researchers]
are satisfied that it may be a particular disease, "a relatively accurate
diagnosis can be obtained in 3 days" without the need to carry out further
analyses.

According to Marin, in the cases recorded so far in Zamora and Leon and
based on published information, there are "several things that match" the
cases registered almost 2 decades ago, and at the same time he reported
that another 2 diseases, bluetongue and hemorrhagic disease of red deer
[epizootic haemorrhagic fever], have been ruled out.

The 1st cases of the "Bierzo virus" have already appeared in the province
of Leon, as confirmed on Monday [9 Aug 2010] by the mayor of the town of
Pozos, Avelino Fernandez, who stated that there have been "not less than 30
dead red deer" in his locality. Added to this number would be the "as many
that have appeared in the locality of Corporales." According to the mayor,
dead animals have also appeared in the villages of Manzaneda and Cunas de
Cabrera, but they have not been able to determine how many. Now the
residents of these villages fear a possible "pandemic" affecting the rest
of the livestock in the area.

For its part, the Junta [provincial government] has confirmed "6 dead deer
in the district of La Cabrera, Leon, on the border Zamora, which might have
died during the last week, and which are already in an advanced state of
decomposition. Thus, the 1st deaths recorded of these ungulates in the
Regional Game Reserve of Sierra de la Culebra and the region of La
Carballeda, now extend to the south west of the province of Leon.

Specifically, the Junta says, "a female was found dead without apparent
cause, or injury, in the locality of Pozos, and 2 more in Corporales.
According to information provided by private guards of the game reserves in
the locality of Morla, another female red deer died last week [week of 2
Aug 2010]. Similarly, in Nogarejas, very close to the border with Zamora,
another 2 females died. However, authorities are reassuring the population
and note that no other deaths have been reported in recent days."

Faced with this situation, environmental agents in the region and
neighboring areas have been instructed to be extremely vigilant in the
detection of dead or diseased specimens of that (red deer) or other
species. Also, veterinarians from the Ministry of Agriculture and Livestock
have performed autopsies and taken samples, which have been sent to the
Regional Animal Health Laboratory in Leon and the Spanish Animal Health
Reference Laboratory in Algete (Madrid), in the same way as was done for
the dead red deer in Zamora."

