[Any undiagnosed die-off in a wild deer population is of concern. The
information contained in these 2 articles is sketchy at best and
ProMED-mail would appreciate a definitive diagnosis as soon as possible.
While there is a possibility that the cause of disease may end up to be
parasitic in nature, such a diagnosis cannot be made from a distance as one
article suggests and it is prudent to wait until necropsies are done on
viable samples. Good gross and histopathology are needed in this instance
and although they made be hard to obtain, at the rate these red deer are
dying, we might have definitive results soon.

We would like to thank our tireless correspondent Susan Baekeland for
finding an excellent reference detailing the previous Spanish experience
with _Elaeophoris schneideri_ infection in red deer, published in the
Journal of Wildlife Diseases in 2000. See
<http://www.jwildlifedis.org/cgi/reprint/36/4/779.pdf> for further details.
- Mod.PC

A photo of a red deer (_Cervus elaphus_) can be seen at
<http://www.sierradebaza.org/Fichas_fauna/04_01_ciervo/img_ciervo_1.jpg>.

The provinces of Zamora and Leon, in north west Castile and Leon, can be
seen on the maps at
<http://blog.willamette.edu/people/klutz/journal/archives/spain_map.jpg>
and the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
<http://healthmap.org/r/02li>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
